4. The past perfect - Learn how to use the past perfect

We had been flatmates for a year before we became a couple.
Action 1 ‚Äì We had been flatmates. Action 2 ‚Äì We became a couple.
One event happened before the other event.

When do we use the past perfect?
When there are two events in the past, we use the past perfect 
(e.g. had gone, had worked) to talk about the event that happened first.

We often use "before", "after", and "already" to show which event happened first.

Event that happened first - She had gone on many dates before (...)
Event that happened next - (...) she met her future husband.

She had had a crush on him for years. - first event
They were officially introduced. - second event

We had already bought a flat before we decided to get married.
"Already" and the past perfect in "we had already bought a flat" show 
that they bought the flat first.

We had already gone on five dates (...) - first event
(...) before I learnt what his job was. - second event

"Already" and the past perfect in "we had already gone on five dates" 
show that first they went on five dates.

How do we form the past perfect?
The past perfect = had (not) + past participle (e.g, eaten, gone, driven, moved)
I had already eaten dinner before my boyfriend phoned.
I had already gone to bed when my girlfriend came back from work.

They had already known they were not compatible before they moved in together.

She had already had a crush on him when they got officially introduced.
We'd been together for 10 years when we realised we were not fully compatible.
Had is often abbreviated to "'d" in everyday English.

Lucy and I went to the same school and took the same school bus every morning. 
Actually, I had been in love with her for two years 
before I sat next to her on that bus and spoke to her.

How did you meet Lucy?
I had been in love with her for two years 
before I sat next to her on that bus and spoke to her.

She helped him on his first day of work.
Robert says he couldn't start the printer and Lina came and just plugged it in.

After she had saved my first day at work, 
I couldn‚Äôt stop thinking about the smile and asked her out.

Marta and Howard were friends before they became a couple.
They had been friends for years 
before they even realised they had feelings for each other.

We had been|'d been friends for years before we even realised we had feelings for each other.
We had already gone to the same parties but then something changed.
We had hung out|'d hung out with our mutual friends before we started dating.

